health problems over long
periods of time.

29:02.307 --> 29:05.978 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But first: the hunt to create
fusion energy.

29:06.011 --> 29:10.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
While many people remain worried
about pursuing
further development of nuclear
power, some

29:10.749 --> 29:16.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
researchers believe nuclear
fusion could hold
the key to clean and plentiful
energy.

29:16.088 --> 29:20.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There have been many false
starts before,
but some scientists see real
reason for hope

29:20.759 --> 29:23.695 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that this path will eventually
pay off.

29:23.729 --> 29:28.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Miles O'Brien has a report for
our weekly
segment The Leading Edge, a
co-production

29:28.100 --> 29:32.137 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in this case with "NOVA" and his
special "The
Nuclear Option."

29:32.170 --> 29:38.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: In Southern
California, this
complex, power-hungry machine is
hard at work

29:38.944 --> 29:44.716 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on a seemingly quixotic mission,
akin to catching
lightning in a bottle.

29:44.750 --> 29:47.085 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It is a plasma generator.

29:47.119 --> 29:52.124 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Its builders hope it's a key
step in the long
journey to the Holy Grail of
energy production:

29:52.157 --> 29:53.892 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
fusion.

29:53.925 --> 29:56.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHL BINDERBAUER, CTO, Tri
Alpha Energy:
Fusion is nature's preferred way
of making

29:56.461 --> 29:58.096 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
power.

29:58.130 --> 30:02.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Michl Binderbauer
is chief
technology officer for a startup
called Tri

30:02.034 --> 30:06.672 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Alpha Energy that is making a
$500 million
bet on fusion.

30:06.705 --> 30:10.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHL BINDERBAUER: Think of this
like a mini-sun,
a very hot mini-sun, and it
radiates.

30:10.709 --> 30:15.147 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's that radiation that is
intercepted
on the surface of the machine,
and then it

30:15.180 --> 30:18.016 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
becomes heat, and then you can
process that
into electricity.

30:18.050 --> 30:23.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The promise, no
less than limitless
power, with virtually no
greenhouse gases

30:23.689 --> 30:27.359 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or radioactive waste.

30:27.392 --> 30:31.363 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If that sounds too good to be
true, it is.

30:31.396 --> 30:34.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
No one knows that better than
nuclear engineer
Steve Dean.

30:34.900 --> 30:37.502 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
STEVE DEAN, Fusion Power
Associates: Fusion
is not low-tech.

30:37.536 --> 30:45.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not going to be easy to
prove that it's
reliable, maintainable,
cost-effective, because

30:45.310 --> 30:47.012 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it is complicated.

30:47.045 --> 30:51.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Dean is president
of Fusion
Power Associates, a foundation
focused on

30:51.717 --> 30:53.585 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
research and education.

30:53.618 --> 30:59.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He joined the fusion industry in
1962, working
for the U.S. Atomic Energy
Commission, which

30:59.491 --> 31:02.728 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
coordinated and funded the U.S.
fusion effort.

31:02.761 --> 31:07.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE DEAN: To me, it seemed
like it was something
I could spend my career on, and
we would have

31:07.432 --> 31:10.502 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
electricity on the grid by the
time I retired.

31:10.535 --> 31:11.503 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

31:11.536 --> 31:13.071 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STEVE DEAN: That's what I
thought.

31:13.105 --> 31:14.873 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, it didn't happen that way.

31:14.906 --> 31:18.510 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Fusion is as old
as the cosmos.

31:18.543 --> 31:22.881 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is the nuclear reaction that
takes place
in our sun and all the other
stars in the

31:22.914 --> 31:24.850 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
universe.

31:24.883 --> 31:30.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In a fusion reaction, hydrogen
atoms collide
at high speed, fusing together,
forming a

31:30.489 --> 31:33.558 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
helium atom, releasing one
neutron.

31:33.592 --> 31:38.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Since the mass of the helium
atom is less
than the combined mass of the
two atoms that

31:38.764 --> 31:42.901 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
collided in the first place,
energy is released.

31:42.934 --> 31:50.575 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The dawn of manmade fusion broke
over the
Pacific in 1952, with the first
explosion

31:50.609 --> 31:51.810 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of a hydrogen bomb.

31:51.843 --> 31:54.312 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHL BINDERBAUER: The hydrogen
bomb was a
quick success.

31:54.346 --> 31:55.814 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so a derivative of that was
euphoria.

31:55.847 --> 31:59.151 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In a few more years, we could do
civilian
energy production out of fusion.

31:59.184 --> 32:03.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And while there were glimmers of
hope along
the way, we all now know,
painfully, that

32:03.288 --> 32:05.257 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
hasn't happened.

32:05.290 --> 32:10.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: In the 1950s and
'60s, researchers
looked for ways to control,
confine and sustain

32:10.729 --> 32:15.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
fusion so that it could be used
as an energy
source.

32:15.033 --> 32:21.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They tried newly invented
lasers, a U.S. design
called stellarator, and then a
Russian design

32:21.239 --> 32:27.913 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
called tokamak, a big circular
racetrack that
uses powerful electromagnets to
suspend and

32:27.946 --> 32:32.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
accelerate particles, prompting
fusion-generating
collisions.

32:32.818 --> 32:35.821 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Over the years, they have
gradually answered
many of the questions.

32:35.854 --> 32:40.592 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE DEAN: Right now, there are
still physics
issues that have to be proven,
but the physics

32:40.625 --> 32:42.394 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is very well-known.

32:42.427 --> 32:46.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The only thing that isn't known
is, when you
do something that's a little bit
more closer

32:46.998 --> 32:50.669 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to a power plant, whether
something new will
show up in the physics.

32:50.702 --> 32:52.204 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You can't really predict that.

32:52.237 --> 32:55.273 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: That's what this
huge project
is all about.

32:55.307 --> 33:01.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is the biggest tokamak ever
designed, under
construction in France, the
International

33:01.546 --> 33:08.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Thermonuclear Experimental
Reactor, or ITER,
a joint project of 35 nations,
including the

33:08.186 --> 33:09.621 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
U.S.,

33:09.654 --> 33:13.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is the first engineering test
of a fusion
power plant.

33:13.692 --> 33:20.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ITER is a $14 billion endeavor
that is six
years late and $10 billion over
budget.

33:20.765 --> 33:26.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is designed to one day use 50
megawatts
of electricity to generate 500
megawatts for

33:26.905 --> 33:28.707 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
15 minutes.

33:28.740 --> 33:31.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE DEAN: At some point, in
order to get
to a power plant, you have to
build what we

33:31.810 --> 33:36.348 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
call an engineering test
reactor, or something
that really works, that's
putting out lots

33:36.381 --> 33:40.385 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of fusion energy and has a lot
of the engineering
that's needed for a power plant.

33:40.418 --> 33:46.992 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And ITER and the tokamak are the
-- is the
only track that's at that stage.

33:47.025 --> 33:49.794 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: Three, two, one, zero.

33:49.828 --> 33:56.301 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: But there is a
lot of fusion
progress on a smaller scale.

33:56.334 --> 34:03.842 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Teams in Germany, China and
South Korea have
recently reported longer,
sustained fusion

34:03.875 --> 34:07.112 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
reactions than ever before.

34:07.145 --> 34:11.283 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tri Alpha is the largest of
about a dozen
startups trying to make it work.

34:11.316 --> 34:14.586 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHL BINDERBAUER: We partner up
with some
of the best and brightest in the
field.

34:14.619 --> 34:18.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Michl Binderbauer
began his
work in academia, but believes
the private

34:18.924 --> 34:21.760 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
sector might have a better
chance of success.

34:21.793 --> 34:22.994 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHL BINDERBAUER: It made us
lean.

34:23.028 --> 34:24.796 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It made us focused.

34:24.829 --> 34:29.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It made us an organization that
was nimble
to react to small changes
quickly and think

34:29.501 --> 34:31.169 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
on our feet very quickly.

34:31.202 --> 34:34.272 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I would attribute part of
our success
to exactly that.

34:34.306 --> 34:40.478 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE DEAN: And they're also
building on many
more years of physics
understanding and progress.

34:40.512 --> 34:46.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so they can be smarter now,
whereas, in
the past, a lot of times, their
ideas were

34:46.251 --> 34:53.458 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
interesting, but there wasn't
any physics
basis for having confidence.

34:53.491 --> 34:58.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The fundamental
fusion problem
is, it is not easy to get nuclei
to collide

34:59.030 --> 35:00.732 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and fuse.

35:00.765 --> 35:04.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They are all positively charged,
so they naturally
repel each other, like two
magnets.

35:04.836 --> 35:09.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHL BINDERBAUER: So, we use
magnetic fields
to provide that magnetic bottle,
if you will,

35:09.607 --> 35:12.844 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
into which you put the charged
clouds of particles.

35:12.877 --> 35:18.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The gas wants to escape and
distribute out,
and we're holding that in with
magnetic force.

35:18.583 --> 35:21.553 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is not like how it's done
in the sun,
where you have massive gravity,
it does the

35:21.586 --> 35:22.554 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
same job.

35:22.587 --> 35:24.055 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, here, it's all
electromagnetic fields.

35:24.089 --> 35:27.792 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It takes a lot of
energy to
create those magnetic fields.

35:27.826 --> 35:33.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, the real challenge in
fusion is creating
plasma that generates more
energy than it

35:33.965 --> 35:36.935 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
takes to make it in the first
place.

35:36.968 --> 35:40.772 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Historically, scientists have
opted to go
big, like ITER.

35:40.805 --> 35:46.411 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVE DEAN: One event makes a
very small amount
of practical energy.

35:46.444 --> 35:49.114 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You have to have billions of
these events.

35:49.147 --> 35:53.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That means you have lots of
things -- these
things happening in a large
volume.

35:53.184 --> 35:58.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Tri Alpha is
taking a different
approach that wouldn't require
such a huge

35:58.456 --> 36:00.225 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
structure.

36:00.258 --> 36:07.399 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The idea is to fire two
football-shaped plasma
clouds at each other at
supersonic speeds.

36:07.432 --> 36:12.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the center of the chamber,
they collide
violently, fusing into a larger
football.

36:12.771 --> 36:19.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Additional particles are fired
at right angles,
making the plasma ball spin like
a well-thrown

36:19.310 --> 36:21.079 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
pass.

36:21.112 --> 36:22.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHL BINDERBAUER: The particles
always come
in like this, and they go into
the rotation

36:23.014 --> 36:24.249 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of the main object.

36:24.282 --> 36:26.684 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, it feeds in like this to
maintain that
rotation rate.

36:26.718 --> 36:32.290 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The rotation
suspends the plasma
in place.

36:32.323 --> 36:36.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are testing constantly,
sometimes 50
times a day.

36:37.028 --> 36:47.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Each shot requires about 20
megawatts of electricity,
enough to power all the lights
and appliances

36:47.072 --> 36:53.878 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in 5,000 homes, but for only a
few-thousandths-of-a-second.

36:53.912 --> 36:58.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Gleaning data from a hot ball of
nothing that
lasts for much, much less than
the blink of

36:58.750 --> 37:02.087 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
an eye requires a lot of clever
testing tools.

37:02.120 --> 37:05.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHL BINDERBAUER: Ultimately,
physics is
an experimental science, right?

37:05.390 --> 37:09.027 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, as such, it relies on
hard-core evidence
coming out of an experiment.

37:09.060 --> 37:13.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the stage where we are at, we
are dabbling
a fine line between learning
what works and

37:13.698 --> 37:16.101 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tweaking that and advancing it
another step.

37:16.134 --> 37:20.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Binderbauer
believes a commercial
fusion system will be available
in a decade.

37:21.005 --> 37:25.710 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MICHL BINDERBAUER: Our
great-great-great-grandkids
are going to live in a world
powered by fusion

37:25.743 --> 37:27.679 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
almost exclusively.

37:27.712 --> 37:33.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: But industry
graybeards like
Steve Dean are less willing to
make such predictions.

37:33.852 --> 37:39.557 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
After all, fusion energy has
remained decades
away for many decades.

37:39.591 --> 37:40.558 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is it inevitable, in your view?

37:40.592 --> 37:41.559 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
STEVE DEAN: Yes.

37:41.593 --> 37:42.660 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Just a matter of
time?

37:42.694 --> 37:43.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVE DEAN: I think it's just a
matter of
time.

37:43.595 --> 37:45.530 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I used to say, in my lifetime.

37:45.563 --> 37:47.265 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Then I started saying in my
children.

37:47.298 --> 37:53.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And now I think, before it's of
wide-scale
use, it being at least my
grandchildren.

37:53.138 --> 37:54.105 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

37:54.139 --> 37:55.940 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
STEVE DEAN: I can't predict.

37:55.974 --> 38:00.845 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Right now, we do
not have an
energy crisis to spur the
effort, but we do

38:00.879 --> 38:04.482 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
have a climate crisis.

38:04.516 --> 38:10.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Fusion remains an alluring, yet
still elusive
way to power the planet the same
way nature

38:10.488 --> 38:11.990 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
does.

38:12.023 --> 38:20.265 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Miles O'Brien, the "PBS
NewsHour," Foothill
Ranch, California.

38:20.298 --> 38:32.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: With just a
couple days left
until the inauguration, much of
the nation's

38:32.443 --> 38:36.714 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
attention is on president-elect
Trump's move
into the White House.

38:36.748 --> 38:42.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But Midtown Manhattan residents
are still
focusing on the gold skyscraper
of Trump Tower,

38:42.887 --> 38:46.124 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which will continue to be a home
for the Trump
family.

38:46.157 --> 38:51.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Producer Rhana Natour looks at
the unprecedented
challenges of securing that
residence and

38:51.763 --> 38:53.631 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the financial fallout.

38:53.665 --> 39:01.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RHANA NATOUR: This is the new
reality along
the storied Fifth Avenue in
Midtown Manhattan,

39:01.105 --> 39:06.044 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
dogs, chains, and intense
security.

39:06.077 --> 39:11.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The president-elect has used
Trump Tower as
a base for transition meetings
since the election,

39:11.216 --> 39:16.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and while he will relocate to
the White House
after the inaugural, his wife,
Melania, and

39:16.087 --> 39:20.558 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
10-year-old son Barron plan to
stay in Trump
Tower through the end of the
school year.

39:20.592 --> 39:24.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Evy Poumpouras is a former
Secret Service
agent.

39:24.562 --> 39:29.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For 12 years, she was part of
the presidential
detail for Presidents Obama,
Clinton and both

39:29.634 --> 39:31.135 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Bushes.

39:31.169 --> 39:36.207 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We are seeing delivery truck
after delivery
truck being searched in and out.

39:36.241 --> 39:38.042 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What is happening here?

39:38.076 --> 39:40.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EVY POUMPOURAS, Former U.S.
Secret Service
Agent: So, we want to control
what's coming

39:40.078 --> 39:42.413 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
into the area of Trump Tower.

39:42.447 --> 39:47.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one of the biggest issues
are large vehicles
that can actually have large
amounts of an

39:47.085 --> 39:48.620 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
explosive.

39:48.653 --> 39:51.556 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And a truck would be a perfect
thing, a perfect
IED, a vehicle device, to use.

39:51.589 --> 39:54.792 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, what they will do is, you
will typically
have the vehicle stopped.

39:54.826 --> 39:58.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They will search the vehicle,
make sure there's
nothing inside the vehicle,
underneath the

39:59.030 --> 40:00.932 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
vehicle, make sure it's clean.

40:00.965 --> 40:07.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RHANA NATOUR: Trump Tower
stretches 57 stories,
with 26 floors of offices, three
retail stores

40:07.138 --> 40:08.740 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and hundreds of tenants.

40:08.773 --> 40:13.544 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is also surrounded by other
skyscrapers,
compounding the security
challenge.

40:13.578 --> 40:17.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EVY POUMPOURAS: Right now,
planes aren't allowed
to fly over Trump Tower, same
thing that happens

40:17.582 --> 40:18.783 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
over at the White House.

40:18.816 --> 40:20.485 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But then you have that variable.

40:20.518 --> 40:21.486 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He's up top.

40:21.519 --> 40:22.587 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He's high on the floor.

40:22.620 --> 40:24.022 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Planes are a concern.

40:24.055 --> 40:27.258 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RHANA NATOUR: And, as technology
evolves,
there are ever greater risks.

40:27.292 --> 40:29.060 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
EVY POUMPOURAS: Drones.

40:29.093 --> 40:32.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Can somebody use a drone, not
just to go up
there and, you know what, I want
to see the

40:32.930 --> 40:34.732 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
future president?

40:34.766 --> 40:38.936 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
You can actually strap
explosives, weapons
to those drones, fly them up,
and then cause

40:38.970 --> 40:40.738 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
harm in that way.

40:40.772 --> 40:46.411 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And then also even
cyber-security, radiation,
contamination in the air,
chemical -- any

40:46.444 --> 40:52.817 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
type of chemical airborne
attack, that's also
an issue.

40:52.850 --> 40:54.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The tower itself, one of the
things we look
at is what we call the HVAC
system, which

40:54.852 --> 40:56.754 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is where the air intake system
is.

40:56.788 --> 40:58.656 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's super dangerous as well.

40:58.690 --> 41:02.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RHANA NATOUR: While the Secret
Service is
working on threats from within
the tower,

41:03.027 --> 41:07.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the New York Police Department
guards the
exterior and directs traffic in
the four-block

41:07.465 --> 41:10.001 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
radius where the vehicles are
being limited.

41:10.034 --> 41:14.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The protective measures are
causing a dramatic
slowdown in business here, where
the rents

41:14.339 --> 41:17.008 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are among the highest in the
world.

41:17.041 --> 41:22.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tiffany and Company reporting
this week that
its Fifth Avenue store dropped
14 percent

41:22.213 --> 41:27.785 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at the end of 2016, in part due
to the traffic
disruption.

41:27.819 --> 41:32.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Robert Smith runs operations for
Uncle Jack's
Steakhouse, which has developed
a faithful

41:32.323 --> 41:37.128 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
following for years on West 56th
Street, within
view of Trump Tower.

41:37.161 --> 41:41.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The owner was so excited by the
Trump win
that he named menu items after
him.

41:41.132 --> 41:43.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT SMITH, Uncle Jack's
Steakhouse: We
were down 20 percent right off
the bat, right

41:43.401 --> 41:45.136 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
after the election.

41:45.169 --> 41:48.873 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Once the security came in,
barricades went
up.

41:48.906 --> 41:51.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
People weren't allowed to walk
into the restaurant
or even near the block.

41:51.743 --> 41:54.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RHANA NATOUR: What have you been
hearing from
your regular customers?

41:54.145 --> 41:58.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT SMITH: Obviously, my
regular clientele
isn't coming in as often as they
used to.

41:58.516 --> 42:02.887 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I had bar clientele at lunch
that would come
every day, but that don't.

42:02.920 --> 42:08.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have a lot of tourists that
come, very
tourist-central-located
neighborhood.

42:08.726 --> 42:16.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And a lot of them don't even
want to get anywhere
near barricades and dogs and
giant police

42:16.033 --> 42:17.201 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
bomb trucks.

42:17.235 --> 42:19.370 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it doesn't make anybody want
to come near
the place.

42:19.404 --> 42:24.242 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RHANA NATOUR: A short distance
away, on Sixth
Avenue, Jimmie Tarzy at Allen M.
Jewelers

42:24.275 --> 42:28.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
says he has been losing 30 to 50
percent on
any given week.

42:28.146 --> 42:32.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He worries about what will
happen to business
if Trump returns to his
penthouse residence

42:32.383 --> 42:33.851 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
each weekend.

42:33.885 --> 42:36.254 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JIMMY TARZY, Allen M. Jewelers:
You have to
take precautionary measures.

42:36.287 --> 42:38.055 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I can understand that.

42:38.089 --> 42:39.891 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I really do.

42:39.924 --> 42:45.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But being the president, or
president-elect,
you have to say to yourself,
you're supposed

42:45.496 --> 42:46.831 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to do for the people.

42:46.864 --> 42:48.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Go live in Washington.

42:48.199 --> 42:52.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RHANA NATOUR: Some are calling
Trump Tower
White House North.

42:52.203 --> 42:57.008 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Exactly how security will be
transformed here
is still a work in progress.

42:57.041 --> 43:01.179 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At a New York City Council
meeting last week,
questions on how to prepare and
who should

43:01.212 --> 43:03.848 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
pay went unanswered by NYPD
officials.

43:03.881 --> 43:08.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: Does the Secret Service
have the right
to close down a street on its
own?

43:08.186 --> 43:09.921 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MAN: I'm not sure.

43:09.954 --> 43:18.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: If the NYPD were to decline
to provide
service in and around Trump
Tower because

43:18.229 --> 43:22.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of cost or lack of reimbursement
or whatever,
what would happen then?

43:22.767 --> 43:25.303 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: I'm unable to answer that
question.

43:25.336 --> 43:29.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN: We have to have some idea
of how much
is it going to cost, because,
right now, we

43:29.841 --> 43:35.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are just spending with an
unlimited credit,
really, and hoping that maybe
the federal

43:35.513 --> 43:37.648 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
government will pay, maybe not.

43:37.682 --> 43:42.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RHANA NATOUR: The NYPD estimates
that, for
every day the president resides
in Trump Tower,

43:42.386 --> 43:45.556 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
it costs the city $500,000.

43:45.590 --> 43:51.062 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So far, Congress has agreed to
reimburse New
York City $7 million for the
cost of providing

43:51.095 --> 43:55.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NYPD security to Trump Tower and
the surrounding
area.

43:55.299 --> 44:01.239 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is far less, however, than
the $35 million
the city initially requested.

44:01.272 --> 44:04.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Councilman Dan Garodnick, who
represents the
Trump Tower neighborhood,
objects.

44:04.475 --> 44:08.779 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAN GARODNICK, New York City
Councilman: Why
is New York City bearing the
cost of security

44:08.813 --> 44:10.648 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for the president-elect?

44:10.681 --> 44:16.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have some very significant
businesses on
Fifth Avenue that employ
hundreds of New Yorkers

44:16.888 --> 44:18.589 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
each.

44:18.623 --> 44:23.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we want to make sure that
these jobs and
these businesses do not become a
casualty

44:23.160 --> 44:24.962 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of the Trump presidency here.

44:24.996 --> 44:29.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RHANA NATOUR: It's a balancing
act between
keeping the legendary business
district humming

44:29.567 --> 44:33.371 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and protecting the first family
living at
the heart of it.

44:33.404 --> 44:41.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In New York City, I'm Rhana
Natour for the
"PBS NewsHour."

44:41.579 --> 44:50.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally tonight,
a conversation
about changing the way we think
about health

44:50.888 --> 44:52.657 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
care.

44:52.690 --> 44:56.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In an article in the latest
issue of "The
New Yorker," Dr. Atul Gawande, a
surgeon and

44:56.961 --> 45:02.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
author, makes the case for the
value of what
he calls incremental medicine to
deal with

45:02.300 --> 45:03.968 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
chronic conditions.

45:04.001 --> 45:08.606 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's the kind of medicine less
heralded than
that using heroic measures.

45:08.639 --> 45:12.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
William Brangham spoke with Dr.
Gawande recently
and asked him how health care is
changing.

45:12.376 --> 45:14.145 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

45:14.178 --> 45:15.947 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ATUL GAWANDE, "The New Yorker":
When you think
about the future of health care
and where

45:15.980 --> 45:21.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we're going at this moment of
debate, there's
a transformation going on that
involves a

45:21.085 --> 45:25.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
recognition that our focus in
medicine has
been on heroic interventions,
like the kind

45:25.856 --> 45:28.192 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that I do now as a surgeon.

45:28.225 --> 45:33.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the biggest gains are coming
right now
from incremental medicine, from
a commitment

45:34.031 --> 45:39.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to the kind of steady, overtime
management
of complex problems like chronic
illnesses

45:39.637 --> 45:42.373 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that can add years to people's
lives.

45:42.406 --> 45:47.311 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But that's work done by some of
the people
with the least resources in our
health care

45:47.345 --> 45:49.213 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
system.

45:49.246 --> 45:51.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, who
practices incremental
medicine in our health care
system today?

45:51.816 --> 45:53.551 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

45:53.584 --> 45:55.753 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ATUL GAWANDE: Well, good
examples, just look
at the list of who the
lowest-paid people

45:55.786 --> 45:56.754 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
are.

45:56.787 --> 45:58.889 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Pediatricians are at the bottom.

45:58.923 --> 46:00.891 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
You would also look at
internists.

46:00.925 --> 46:02.727 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You would look at psychiatrists.

46:02.760 --> 46:08.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
You would look at family
physicians, HIV specialists.

46:08.599 --> 46:14.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
People who take care of chronic
illnesses
by seeing people carefully over
time, those

46:14.538 --> 46:16.774 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are the people who get the least
money.

46:16.807 --> 46:23.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The people who have the most are
people like
orthopedic surgeons,
interventional cardiologists.

46:23.948 --> 46:29.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And my point isn't that -- you
know, that
we're -- that there is something
wrong with

46:29.553 --> 46:31.355 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
heroism.

46:31.389 --> 46:37.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My own son has a congenital
heart condition,
where his life was saved by a
cardiac surgeon

46:37.495 --> 46:41.132 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
stepping in at 11 days of life
to save his
life.

46:41.165 --> 46:47.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But he is now 21 years old
because of constant
monitoring and working with him
with a primary

46:47.872 --> 46:53.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
care physician and people who
controlled his
blood pressure, recognized
problems before

46:53.244 --> 46:57.281 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they arose, dealt with learning
issues that
were related to his condition.

46:57.314 --> 47:01.786 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's the only reason now
that he's getting
to live a long and healthy life.

47:01.819 --> 47:03.587 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's what we're not rewarding.

47:03.621 --> 47:08.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They don't have the kind of
resources and
commitment that we are giving to
people like

47:08.726 --> 47:10.761 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
me.

47:10.795 --> 47:13.898 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have millions of dollars of
equipment available
to me when I go to work every
day in an operating

47:13.931 --> 47:15.399 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
room.

47:15.433 --> 47:19.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The clinicians who keep my son
going are lucky
if they can have a nurse.

47:19.437 --> 47:25.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, if that
care is so valuable,
why are the incentives seemingly
going in

47:25.176 --> 47:26.143 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the opposite direction?

47:26.177 --> 47:27.978 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

47:28.012 --> 47:30.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ATUL GAWANDE: It's mainly
because our health
system was built at a time when
we couldn't

47:30.581 --> 47:32.383 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
really do this kind of work.

47:32.416 --> 47:38.222 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Go back to the '30s, '40s, '50s,
and it was
the discovery of heroic
interventions, the

47:38.255 --> 47:47.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ability to cure people with
penicillin or
do an operation to stop disease
that was what

47:47.398 --> 47:49.166 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
saved the day.

47:49.200 --> 47:54.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Primary care physicians couldn't
do all that
much that really demonstrated a
difference.

47:54.338 --> 47:59.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now we have had the data to
track people for
a long time, the computational
power that

47:59.110 --> 48:05.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
recognized, you know what, high
blood pressure,
which we didn't even know was a
huge problem,

48:05.349 --> 48:09.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we discovered that it afflicts a
third of
all Americans, and it's our
biggest killer,

48:09.954 --> 48:15.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that years down in the future,
that that is
our cause of everything from not
only heart

48:15.993 --> 48:20.197 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
disease, but dementia and of
kidney disease.

48:20.231 --> 48:26.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, you know, the people who
control and work
with you to control your blood
pressure, they're

48:26.670 --> 48:29.106 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not rewarded for doing that or
to be innovative
about doing that.

48:29.140 --> 48:36.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the result is half of
Americans have uncontrolled
high blood pressure, despite
seeing clinicians.

48:36.213 --> 48:41.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The Affordable
Care Act
tried to move the needle in this
direction,

48:41.085 --> 48:45.222 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to put more incentives towards
the exact kind
of care that you're talking
about.

48:45.256 --> 48:47.992 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How successful has that been,
that effort
been?

48:48.025 --> 48:49.126 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

48:49.160 --> 48:51.061 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ATUL GAWANDE: Here's what I
would describe
it as.

48:51.095 --> 48:56.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We now have 30 percent, for
example, of Medicare
patients who are seeing doctors
who are rewarded

48:56.834 --> 49:01.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for doing this kind of work,
which is a dramatic
change from six or seven years
ago.

49:01.238 --> 49:06.677 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the Affordable Care Act has
pushed this
direction down the road.

49:06.710 --> 49:14.518 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It has also offered protections
that allow
for preexisting conditions, as
people know,

49:14.552 --> 49:19.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that if you have preexisting
conditions like
my son does, that you're
provided coverage

49:19.990 --> 49:22.193 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and you can maintain steady
coverage.

49:22.226 --> 49:28.499 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
